04612nam a22005655i 9780889208759DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892087597 a10.51644/97808892087592doi  a(DE-B1597)667376  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBL41b.B69 2001 7aEDU0150002bisacsh04a200a200/.71a200/.71/17151 aBowlby, Paul W.R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReligious Studies in Atlantic Canada :bA State-of-the-Art Review /cPaul W.R. Bowlby. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudy of Religion in Canada ;v600tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tThe Religious Roots of the Universities in the Atlantic Provinces -- tDepartments and Degree Programs in Religious Studies -- tThe Curriculum in Religious Studies -- tFaculty in Religious Studies -- tConclusion -- tConclusion 1987 -- tAppendix 2 -- tDocuments Provided by Religious Studies Departments -- tDocuments from the Nova Scotia Council on Higher Education -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tSeries Published by Wilfrid Laurier University Press for the Canadian Corporation for Studies in Religion / Corporation Canadienne des Sciences Religieuses0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is “Religious Studies” and what is its future in Atlantic Canada? How have universities founded by Roman Catholic and Protestant denominations, and public universities, differed as they approached the study of religious life and traditions? Religious Studies in Atlantic Canada surveys the history and place of the study of religion within Canadian universities. Following a historical introduction to the public and denominationally founded universities in the Atlantic region, the book situates the departments of religious studies in relation to the distinctive characteristics of the various universities in the region, focusing on curriculum, research and teaching. Bowlby examines the current strengths of the religious studies departments in Atlantic Canada, and where those departments are fragile, i.e., where departments have thrived because of careful long-term planning, as well as where crises of retirements have radically affected the size and strength of departments. In conclusion Bowlby suggests strategies for future survival and growth in the field of religious studies. Religious Studies in Atlantic Canada is the last of a six-part series on the state of the art of religious studies in Canada, a unique account of the regional differences in the development of religious studies in Canada. Written for anyone interested in the teaching of religion as well as the specialist, the book provides an introduction and an overview of religious studies curricula, faculty research, and teaching areas at the region’s universities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aReligionxStudy and teaching (Higher)zAtlantic Provinces. 0aTheologyxStudy and teaching (Higher)zAtlantic Provinces. 4aEducation. 4aReligion. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh1 aFaulkner, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920875940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208759423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208759/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP U